-- U.K. Stocks Rally to Five-Month High as Banks Rise; RBS Surges
-- B y   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 2012-01-19T17:12:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-19/ftse-100-stocks-are-little-changed-before-debt-auctions-rbs-shares-gain.html
  U.K. stocks  jumped to a five-month
high, led by a rally in lenders, after Spain and France sold
bonds at lower yields and results from Bank of America Corp. to
Morgan Stanley beat analysts’ estimates.  Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc (RBS) ,  Barclays Plc (BARC)  and Lloyds
Banking Group all surged more than 8 percent. International
Consolidated Airlines Group SA paced European airlines higher
after Qatar Airways Ltd. said it is examining a potential
acquisition in the region.  William Hill Plc (WMH)  soared 6.3 percent
after the bookmaker said its full-year performance is in line
with analysts’ estimates.  The benchmark  FTSE 100  Index gained 38.78, or 0.7 percent,
to 5,741.15 at the close in  London , its highest level since Aug.
1. The FTSE All-Share Index climbed 0.8 percent, while Ireland’s
ISEQ Index jumped 2.4 percent as shares of Readymix Plc soared.  “Bears are still surprised by the strength in equity
markets and today served as yet another example of risk
appetite,” said  Angus Campbell , head of sales at Capital
Spreads. “ Whilst the euro zone battles continue to rumble on
in the background, some investors remain convinced that equities
represent good value.”  Stocks climbed as France auctioned 7.97 billion euros of
two-, three- and four-year notes in its first sale of medium-and
long-term debt after losing its AAA rating at  Standard & Poor’s 
on Jan. 13.  Spain  sold 6.61 billion euros of bonds maturing in
2016, 2019 and 2022, exceeding its target of 4.5 billion euros.  Bank of America  Shares extended gains after Bank of America Corp., the
second-largest U.S. lender, swung to a fourth-quarter profit as
the company sold assets and built capital faster than expected,
while Morgan Stanley reported a lower-than-estimated loss. The
bank’s fourth-quarter loss of 15 cents per share topped
analysts’ estimates for a loss of 57 cents a share.  A  gauge of U.K. bank shares  advanced for an eighth day, its
longest stretch of gains since 2005.  RBS surged 8.9 percent to 27.06 pence, Barclays increased
10 percent to 221.35 pence, Lloyds soared 9.1 percent to 32.27
pence and  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA) ,  Europe ’s largest bank, advanced 4
percent to 536.4 pence.  Lenders also advanced climbed as the cost for European
banks to borrow in dollars stayed at its lowest level in five
months, according to a money-market indicator. The three-month
cross-currency basis swap, the rate banks pay to convert euro
interest payments into dollars, was 77 basis points below the
euro interbank-offered rate.  IAG,  Aer Lingus (AERL)   Elsewhere, IAG, the parent company of British Airways,
jumped 6.5 percent to 165.5 pence in London, while Aer Lingus
Group Plc rose 7.6 percent to 71 euro cents in Dublin trading.  European airlines climbed after Qatar Airways’ Chief
Executive Officer Akbar Al Baker said the company is examining a
potential acquisition in Europe. It purchased a stake in freight
operator Cargolux International SA last year.  The Gulf region’s second-largest airline has “identified”
one or more targets as it searches for takeover prospects, Al
Baker said in a briefing at the Bahrain Air Show.  William Hill rallied 6.3 percent to 223 pence after the
U.K. bookmaker said its full-year performance is in line with
analysts’ estimates. The  company  forecast revenue to grow 6
percent and operating profit to reach about 274 million pounds
($424 million).  ABF, Land Securities  Associated British Foods Plc (ABF)  gained 1.9 percent to 1,159
pence after the U.K. sugar producer that owns the Primark
clothing business reported a 12 percent increase in first-
quarter revenue on “exceptional” retail sales and rising sugar
prices in Europe.  Land Securities Group Plc (LAND)  advanced 5.7 percent to 679.5
pence after Exane BNP Paribas raised its recommendation for the
real-estate investment trust to “outperform” from “neutral.”  AstraZeneca Plc (AZN)  paced declining shares after its
experimental diabetes drug failed to win backing from U.S.
regulators. The U.K.’s second-biggest drugmaker fell 1.3 percent
to 3,070 pence.  Pearson Plc (PSON)  lost 1.3 percent to 1,230 pence after analysts
said that the owner of the Financial Times won’t be able to
repeat tax gains and low interest charges that helped to boost
last year’s profit.  In Ireland,  Readymix Plc (RYX)  soared 533 percent to 19 euro
cents after the Irish cement distributor received an approach
from Cemex SAB to buy the shares it doesn’t already own in the
company for 22 euro cents each. Some 6,000 shares traded.  To contact the reporter on this story:
